INSERT INTO `questions` (`QuestionID`, `ExamBoard`, `Subject`, `ExamUnit`, `ExamYear`, `ExamMonth`, `QuestionNumber`, `QuestionContent`) VALUES
(22, 'Edexcel', 'Mathematics', 'FP3', 2014, 'Jun', 6, '*[In this question you may use the appropriate trigonometric identities on page 6 of the pink Mathematical Formulae and Statistical Tables.]*\r\n\r\nThe points $P(3\\cos{\\alpha}, 2\\sin{\\alpha})$ and $Q(3\\cos{\\beta},2\\sin{\\beta})$, where $\\alpha\\neq\\beta$. lie on the ellipse with equation\r\n$$\\frac{x^2}{9}+\\frac{y^2}{4}=1$$\r\n* Show the equation of the chord $PQ$ is\r\n$$\\frac{x}{3}\\cos{\\frac{(\\alpha+\\beta)}{2}}+\\frac{y}{2}\\sin{\\frac{(\\alpha+\\beta)}{2}}=\\cos{\\frac{(\\alpha-\\beta)}{2}}$$\r\n**(4)**\r\n* Write down the coordinates of the mid-point of $PQ$.\r\n**(1)**\r\n\r\nGiven that the gradient, $m$, of the chord $PQ$ is a constant,\r\n* show that the centre of the chord lies on a line \r\n$y=-kx$$\r\nexpressing $k$ in terms of $m$.\r\n**(5)**'),
(23, 'Edexcel', 'Mathematics', 'FP3', 2014, 'Jun', 5, 'Given that $y=\\arctanh{\\dfrac{x}{\\sqrt{1+x^2}}}$\r\n\r\nshow that $\\dfrac{\\d y}{\\d x}=\\dfrac{1}{\\sqrt{1+x^2}}$\r\n**(4)**'),
(24, 'Edexcel', 'Mathematics', 'FP3', 2014, 'Jun', 4, 'Using the definitions of hyperbolic functions in terms of exponentials,\r\n* show that $$\\sech^2{x}=1-\\tanh^2{x}$$\r\n**(3)**\r\n* solve the equation $$4\\sinh{x}-3\\cosh{x}=3$$\r\n**(4)**'),
(25, 'Edexcel', 'Mathematics', 'FP3', 2014, 'Jun', 2, '$$\\mathbf{M}=\\begin{pmatrix}\r\n1 & 0 & 2 \\\\\\\r\n0 & 4 & 1 \\\\\\\r\n0 & 5 & 0 \\end{pmatrix}$$\r\n\r\n* Show that matrix $\\mathbf{M}$ is not orthogonal.\r\n**(2)**\r\n* Using algebra, show that $1$ is an eigenvalue of $\\mathbf{M}$ and find the other two eigenvalues of $\\mathbf{M}$.\r\n**(5)**\r\n* Find an eigenvector of $\\mathbf{M}$ which corresponds to the eigenvalue $1$\r\n**(2)**\r\n\r\nThe transformation $M:\\mathbb{R}^3\\rightarrow\\mathbb{R}^3$ is represented by the matrix $\\mathbf{M}$.\r\n* Find a cartesian equation of the image, under this transformation, of the line\r\n$$x=\\frac{y}{2}=\\frac{z}{-1}$$\r\n**(4)**'),
(26, 'Edexcel', 'Mathematics', 'FP3', 2014, 'Jun', 7, 'A circle $C$ with centre $O$ and radius $r$ has cartesian equation $x^2+y^2=r^2$ where $r$ is a constant.\r\n* Show that $1+\\left(\\dfrac{\\d y}{\\d x}\\right)^2=\\dfrac{r^2}{r^2-x^2}$\r\n**(3)**\r\n* Show that the surface area of the sphere generated by rotating $C$ through $\\pi$ radians about the $x$-axis is $4\\pi r^2$.\r\n**(5)**\r\n* Write down the length of the arc of the curve $y=\\sqrt{1-x^2}$ from $x=0$ to $x=1$\r\n**(1)**'),
(27, 'Edexcel', 'Mathematics', 'FP3', 2014, 'Jun', 8, 'The position vectors of the points $A$, $B$ and $C$ from a fixed origin $O$ are\r\n$$\\mathbf{a}=\\mathbf{i}-\\mathbf{j},\\ \\mathbf{b}=\\mathbf{i}+\\mathbf{j}+\\mathbf{k},\\ \\mathbf{c}=2\\mathbf{j}+\\mathbf{k}$$\r\nrespectively.\r\n* Using vector products, find the area of the triangle $ABC$.\r\n**(4)**\r\n* Show that $\\frac{1}{6}\\mathbf{a}.(\\mathbf{b}\\times\\mathbf{c})=0$\r\n**(3)**\r\n* Hence or otherwise, state what can be deduced about the vectors $\\mathbf{a}$, $\\mathbf{b}$ and $\\mathbf{c}$.\r\n**(1)**'),
(28, 'Edexcel', 'Mathematics', 'FP3', 2014, 'Jun', 1, 'The line $l$ passes through the point $P(2, 1, 3)$ and is perpendicular to the plane $\\Pi$ whose vector equation is\r\n$$\\mathbf{r}.(\\mathbf{i}-2\\mathbf{j}-\\mathbf{k})=3$$\r\nFind\r\n* a vector equation of the line $l$,\r\n**(2)**\r\n* the position vector of the point where $l$ meets $\\Pi$.\r\n**(4)**\r\n* Hence find the perpendicular distance of $P$ from $\\Pi$.\r\n**(2)**'),
(29, 'Edexcel', 'Mathematics', 'FP3', 2014, 'Jun', 9, '\r\n$$I_n=\\int{(x^2+1)^{-n}}\\d x,\\ n>0$$\r\n* Show that, for $n>0$\r\n$$I_ {n+1}=\\dfrac{x(x^2+1)^{-n}}{2n}+\\dfrac{2n-1}{2n}I_n$$\r\n**(5)**\r\n* Find $I_2$\r\n**(3)**\r\n'),
(30, 'Edexcel', 'Mathematics', 'FP3', 2014, 'Jun', 3, 'Using calculus, find the exact value of\r\n* $\\int_1^2{\\dfrac{1}{x^2-2x+3}}\\d x$\r\n**(4)**\r\n* $\\int_0^1{e^{2x}\\sinh{x}}\\d x$\r\n**(4)**'),
(31, 'Edexcel', 'Mathematics', 'FP2', 2014, 'Jun', 1, '* Express $\\dfrac{2}{(r+2)(r+4)}$ in partial fractions\r\n**(1)**\r\n* Hence show that $$\\sum_{r=1}^n\\dfrac{2}{(r+2)(r+4)}=\\dfrac{n(7n+25)}{12(n+3)(n+4)}$$\r\n**(5)**'),
(32, 'Edexcel', 'Mathematics', 'FP2', 2014, 'Jun', 2, 'Use algebra to find the set of values of $x$ for which\r\n$$|3x^2-19x+20|<2x+2$$\r\n**(6)**'),
(33, 'Edexcel', 'Mathematics', 'FP2', 2014, 'Jun', 3, '$$y=\\sqrt{8+e^x}$$\r\nFind the series expansion for $y$ in ascending powers of $x$, up to and including the term in $x^2$, giving each coefficient in its simplest form.\r\n**(8)**'),
(34, 'Edexcel', 'Mathematics', 'FP2', 2014, 'Jun', 4, '* Use de Moivre''s theorem to show that\r\n$$\\cos{6\\theta}=32\\cos^6{\\theta}-48\\cos^4{\\theta}+18\\cos^2{\\theta}-1$$\r\n**(5)**\r\n* Hence solve for $0\\leq\\theta\\leq\\frac{\\pi}{2}$\r\n$$64\\cos^6{\\theta}-96\\cos^4{\\theta}+36\\cos^2{\\theta}-3=0$$\r\ngiving your answers as exact multiples of $\\pi$\r\n**(5)**'),
(35, 'Edexcel', 'Mathematics', 'FP2', 2014, 'Jun', 5, '* Find the general solution of the differential equation\r\n$$\\dfrac{\\d^2y}{\\d x^2}+2\\dfrac{\\d y}{\\d x}+10y=27e^{-x}$$\r\n**(6)**\r\n* Find the particular solution that satisfies $y=0$ and $\\dfrac{\\d y}{\\d x}=0$ when $x=0$\r\n**(6)**'),
(36, 'Edexcel', 'Mathematics', 'FP2', 2014, 'Jun', 6, 'The transformation $T$ from the $z$-plane, where $z=x+\\mathrm{i}y$, to the $w$-plane, where $w=u+\\mathrm{i}v$, is given by\r\n$$w=\\dfrac{4(1-\\mathrm{i})z-8\\mathrm{i}}{2(-1+\\mathrm{i})z-\\mathrm{i}},\\ z\\neq\\frac{1}{4}-\\frac{1}{4}\\ \\mathrm{i}$$\r\nThe transformation $T$ maps the points on the line $l$ with equation $y=x$ in the $z$-plane to a circle $C$ in the $w$-plane.\r\n* Show that\r\n$$w=\\dfrac{ax^2+bx\\mathrm{i}+c}{16x^2+1}$$\r\nwhere $a$, $b$ and $c$ are real constants to be found.\r\n**(6)**\r\n* Hence show that the circle $C$ has equation\r\n$$(u-3)^2+v^2=k^2$$\r\nwhere $k$ is a constant to be found.\r\n**(4)**'),
(37, 'Edexcel', 'Mathematics', 'FP2', 2014, 'Jun', 7, '* Show that the substitution $v=y^{-3}$ transforms the differential equation\r\n$$x\\dfrac{\\d y}{\\d x}+y=2x^4y^4\\ \\ \\ \\mathrm{(I)}$$\r\ninto the differential equation\r\n$$\\dfrac{\\d v}{\\d x}-\\dfrac{3v}{x}=-6x^3\\ \\ \\ \\mathrm{(II)}$$\r\n**(5)**\r\n* By solving differential equation $\\mathrm{(II)}$, find a general solution of differential equation $\\mathrm{(I)}$ in the form $y^3=\\mathrm{f}(x)$.\r\n**(6)**'),
(38, 'Edexcel', 'Mathematics', 'FP2', 2014, 'Jun', 8, '![Image not found][Figure 1]\r\n\r\nFigure 1 shows a sketch of part of the curve $C$ with polar equation\r\n$$r=1+\\tan{\\theta},\\ 0\\leq\\theta<\\frac{\\pi}{2}$$\r\n\r\nThe tangent to the curve $C$ at the point $P$ is perpendicular to the initial line.\r\n* Find the polar coordinates of the point $P$.\r\n**(5)**\r\n\r\nThe point $Q$ lies on the curve $C$, where $\\theta=\\frac{\\pi}{3}$\r\n\r\nThe shaded region $R$ is bounded by $OP$, $OQ$ and the curve $C$, as show in Figure 1\r\n* Find the exact area of $R$, giving your answer in the form\r\n$$\\frac{1}{2}(\\ln{p}+\\sqrt{q}+r)$$\r\nwhere $p$, $q$ and $r$ are integers to be found.\r\n**(7)**\r\n\r\n[Figure 1]: data:image/png;base64,\r\n');

